    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper proposes a new gravitational wave detector design\u2014called a Pyramid interferometer\u2014that could directly detect the \"handedness\" (chirality) of cosmological gravitational waves, a signature of parity-violating physics in the early universe that no current or planned detector can cleanly access. The review board found the geometric concept genuinely novel and potentially important for next-generation detector planning. However, the board is divided on whether the central mathematical claim\u2014that the proposed geometry automatically isolates the chiral signal from the unpolarized background\u2014actually holds for the described configuration. That dispute, along with an unverified assumption that a 1-km above-ground tower would achieve underground-level noise performance, must be resolved before the paper's sensitivity forecasts can be trusted.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper argues that adding one or two non-coplanar arms to the triangular Einstein Telescope layout creates a detector pair whose overlap reduction functions satisfy \u03b3_I = 0 and \u03b3_V \u2260 0 simultaneously\u2014yielding exact geometric separation of the Stokes-I intensity and Stokes-V circular-polarization channels. The dispute among reviewers centers on whether the specific arm geometry of Eq. (13) actually achieves this: Gemini's tensor calculation finds the detector tensors are heavily aligned for any small-tilt pyramid, giving large \u03b3_I, while Codex argues (after accessing the PDF) that the leading-order detector-tensor contraction does cancel for those specific arm vectors. If \u03b3_I \u2260 0, the SNR formula (Eq. 20) omits the noise penalty of subtracting a much larger Stokes-I background, potentially invalidating Fig. 3. An independent concern raised by Claude is that \u03b3_V is suppressed by O(h/L) for the underground Minimal Pyramid (h/L ~ 1\u20133%), a fundamental trade-off the paper does not discuss. The Tower-Extended variant's noise analysis is acknowledged by all reviewers to be insufficient, relying on the underground ET noise budget without quantifying tower-specific noise sources."
    }
